Load Required Packages:

library(ggplot2)
library(dplyr)

1 Exercise 1: Modify Plot Background and Grid

Dataset: mtcars (available within R).

Task: Create a scatter plot of mpg against hp from the mtcars dataset. Adjust the theme to: 1. Set the plot background to “lightblue”. 2. Change major grid lines to “white”. 3. Remove minor grid lines and axis ticks.

Functions to Use: ggplot(), aes(), geom_point(), theme(), element_rect(), element_line(), element_blank()

Solution:

plot1 <- ggplot(mtcars, aes(x = hp, y = mpg)) +
  geom_point() +
  theme(
    plot.background = element_rect(fill = "lightblue"),
    panel.grid.major = element_line(color = "white"),
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(),
    axis.ticks = element_blank()
  )

print(plot1)

2 Exercise 2: Change Title and Axis Text Styles

Dataset: diamonds (available within the ggplot2 package).

Task: Plot price against carat from the diamonds dataset. Customize the theme to: 1. Bolden and color the plot title “red”. 2. Italicize the axis text.

Functions to Use: ggplot(), aes(), geom_point(), ggtitle(), theme(), element_text()

Solution:

plot2 <- ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = carat, y = price)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +
  ggtitle("Price vs Carat") +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", color = "red"),
    axis.text = element_text(face = "italic")
  )

print(plot2)

3 Exercise 3: Alter Legend Properties

Dataset: iris (available within R).

Task: Develop a scatter plot of Sepal.Length against Sepal.Width, colored by Species. Adjust the theme to: 1. Place the legend at the bottom. 2. Fill the legend background with “grey90”. 3. Change legend title text to be bold and blue.

Functions to Use: ggplot(), aes(), geom_point(), theme(), element_rect(), element_text()

Solution:

plot3 <- ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Width, y = Sepal.Length, color = Species)) +
  geom_point() +
  theme(
    legend.position = "bottom",
    legend.background = element_rect(fill = "grey90"),
    legend.title = element_text(face = "bold", color = "blue")
  )

print(plot3)

4 Exercise 4: Adjust Axis Line Appearance and Title Position

Dataset: Fictitious dataset of monthly sales.

Task: Plot sales across months. Customize the theme to: 1. Make axis lines thicker. 2. Center-align the plot title.

Load Dataset:

sales_data <- data.frame(
  month = month.abb,
  sales = c(500, 520, 515, 530, 535, 545, 560, 575, 580, 590, 600, 610)
)

Functions to Use: ggplot(), aes(), geom_line(), geom_point(), ggtitle(), theme(), element_line()

Solution:

plot4 <- ggplot(sales_data, aes(x = month, y = sales)) +
  geom_line(group = 1) +
  geom_point() +
  ggtitle("Monthly Sales") +
  theme(
    axis.line = element_line(size = 2),
    plot.title.position = "plot"
  )
## Warning: The `size` argument of `element_line()` is deprecated as of ggplot2 3.4.0.
## ℹ Please use the `linewidth` argument instead.
## This warning is displayed once every 8 hours.
## Call `lifecycle::last_lifecycle_warnings()` to see where this warning was generated.
print(plot4)

5 Exercise 5: Adjusting Strip Text in Facets

Dataset: mpg (available within the ggplot2 package).

Task: Create a scatter plot of hwy against displ from the mpg dataset. Facet the plot by class. Adjust the theme to: 1. Color the strip text in “white”. 2. Set the strip background to “darkblue”.

Functions to Use: ggplot(), aes(), geom_point(), facet_wrap(), theme(), element_text(), element_rect()

Solution:

plot5 <- ggplot(mpg, aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  geom_point() +
  facet_wrap(~class) +
  theme(
    strip.text = element_text(color = "white"),
    strip.background = element_rect(fill = "darkblue")
  )

print(plot5)

6 Exercise 6: Modify Legend Key Shapes

Dataset: iris (available within R).

Task: Create a scatter plot of Sepal.Length against Sepal.Width, colored by Species. Adjust the theme to: 1. Use square shape keys in the legend.

Functions to Use: ggplot(), aes(), geom_point(), theme(), guide_legend(), override.aes

Solution:

plot6 <- ggplot(iris, aes(x = Sepal.Width, y = Sepal.Length, color = Species)) +
  geom_point() +
  theme(
    legend.key = element_rect()
  ) +
  guides(
    color = guide_legend(override.aes = list(shape = 15))
  )

print(plot6)

7 Exercise 7: Custom Axis Ticks and Labels

Dataset: diamonds (available within the ggplot2 package).

Task: Plot price against carat from the diamonds dataset. Customize the theme to: 1. Increase the size of x-axis tick marks. 2. Color y-axis tick text to “red”.

Functions to Use: ggplot(), aes(), geom_point(), theme(), element_line(), element_text()

Solution:

plot7 <- ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = carat, y = price)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +
  theme(
    axis.ticks.x = element_line(size = 2),
    axis.text.y = element_text(color = "red")
  )

print(plot7)

8 Exercise 8: Modify Plot Margins

Dataset: airquality (available within R).

Task: Plot Wind against Temp. Adjust the theme to: 1. Increase the margin around the entire plot.

Functions to Use: ggplot(), aes(), geom_point(), theme(), margin()

Solution:

plot8 <- ggplot(airquality, aes(x = Wind, y = Temp)) +
  geom_point() +
  theme(
    plot.margin = margin(2, 2, 2, 2, "cm")
  )

print(plot8)

9 Exercise 9: Remove Plot Labels

Dataset: Fictitious dataset of weekly sales.

Task: Plot sales across weeks. Customize the theme to: 1. Remove axis title and plot title.

Load Dataset:

sales_weekly <- data.frame(
  week = 1:52,
  sales = rnorm(52, 550, 25)
)

Functions to Use: ggplot(), aes(), geom_line(), theme(), element_blank()

Solution:

plot9 <- ggplot(sales_weekly, aes(x = week, y = sales)) +
  geom_line() +
  ggtitle("Weekly Sales") +
  theme(
    plot.title = element_blank(),
    axis.title.x = element_blank(),
    axis.title.y = element_blank()
  )

print(plot9)
